1
00:00:00,435 --> 00:00:03,518
(audience murmuring)

2
00:00:06,600 --> 00:00:08,520
- [Ann] Okay, why don't
you all take your seats.

3
00:00:08,520 --> 00:00:10,440
Come and take your seats.

4
00:00:10,440 --> 00:00:11,880
Good afternoon everybody.

5
00:00:11,880 --> 00:00:13,200
My name's Ann Harrison.

6
00:00:13,200 --> 00:00:15,960
I'm the dean of the
Haas School of Business.

7
00:00:15,960 --> 00:00:19,200
Welcome to today's Dean Speaker Series.

8
00:00:19,200 --> 00:00:21,120
It is co-sponsored

9
00:00:21,120 --> 00:00:24,540
with the Center for
Social Sector Leadership,

10
00:00:24,540 --> 00:00:26,760
otherwise known as CSSL.

11
00:00:26,760 --> 00:00:31,020
Nora here who runs it
is sitting right here.

12
00:00:31,020 --> 00:00:33,450
I am absolutely thrilled

13
00:00:33,450 --> 00:00:37,741
to introduce our guest
today, Blake Mycoskie.

14
00:00:37,741 --> 00:00:41,400
Blake's story is a really powerful one.

15
00:00:41,400 --> 00:00:46,080
He was on a trip in Argentina in 2006

16
00:00:46,080 --> 00:00:47,460
and while he was there,

17
00:00:47,460 --> 00:00:50,130
he saw many children who had no shoes

18
00:00:50,130 --> 00:00:52,650
and he was deeply affected

19
00:00:52,650 --> 00:00:54,543
by how difficult their lives were.

20
00:00:55,710 --> 00:01:00,420
And so he decided to create Toms Shoes.

21
00:01:00,420 --> 00:01:05,340
And in doing so, he created
the one for one business model.

22
00:01:05,340 --> 00:01:09,060
And that's a model where a
customer, by buying a product,

23
00:01:09,060 --> 00:01:12,480
helps someone else in
need every time they buy.

24
00:01:12,480 --> 00:01:14,790
And that was a complete revolution

25
00:01:14,790 --> 00:01:19,380
in the way to do for profit business.

26
00:01:19,380 --> 00:01:22,110
Amazingly, over its lifetime,

27
00:01:22,110 --> 00:01:27,110
Toms has provided over
96 million pairs of shoes

28
00:01:28,380 --> 00:01:29,534
for children around the world.

29
00:01:29,534 --> 00:01:32,784
(audience applauding)

30
00:01:35,920 --> 00:01:40,380
Since then, Tom's expanded into
other areas of vital needs,

31
00:01:40,380 --> 00:01:44,163
for example, eyewear and safe water.

32
00:01:45,180 --> 00:01:47,280
Now, Blake didn't stop there.

33
00:01:47,280 --> 00:01:51,390
He published a book, "Start
Something That Matters."

34
00:01:51,390 --> 00:01:54,720
And every time that book sells one copy,

35
00:01:54,720 --> 00:01:59,550
he donates a child's book to a child.

36
00:01:59,550 --> 00:02:01,110
So that's really amazing.

37
00:02:01,110 --> 00:02:03,090
His current ventures include

38
00:02:03,090 --> 00:02:06,840
co-founding a wellness program Made For,

39
00:02:06,840 --> 00:02:09,270
and his philanthropic endeavors

40
00:02:09,270 --> 00:02:13,650
include working in the area
of legalizing psychedelics,

41
00:02:13,650 --> 00:02:16,950
hopefully we'll hear a little
bit about that today too.

42
00:02:16,950 --> 00:02:19,770
We're incredibly fortunate today

43
00:02:19,770 --> 00:02:22,560
to have such a trailblazer here

44
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:25,920
working in the area of
socially responsible business

45
00:02:25,920 --> 00:02:28,650
and area that Haas excels in

46
00:02:28,650 --> 00:02:30,930
and that we're passionate about.

47
00:02:30,930 --> 00:02:33,750
Blake, our students have
so much to learn from you,

48
00:02:33,750 --> 00:02:37,920
I just wanna thank you once
again for coming to speak today

49
00:02:37,920 --> 00:02:40,623
to give your insights to our community.

50
00:02:41,610 --> 00:02:45,660
So just some quick
housekeeping, when you sat down,

51
00:02:45,660 --> 00:02:48,870
you might have noticed a
note card on your seat.

52
00:02:48,870 --> 00:02:52,800
If a question occurs to
you, write down the question

53
00:02:52,800 --> 00:02:55,200
while you're listening to the Q&A

54
00:02:55,200 --> 00:03:00,200
and then you can hand it
to our assistants here,

55
00:03:00,540 --> 00:03:02,280
my colleagues, they'll be collecting them

56
00:03:02,280 --> 00:03:05,040
and then there'll be
time starting about 1:10

57
00:03:05,040 --> 00:03:06,063
for some Q&A.

58
00:03:07,830 --> 00:03:11,550
So now I'm going to turn
over the session today

59
00:03:11,550 --> 00:03:14,880
to two students who will be doing the Q&A,

60
00:03:14,880 --> 00:03:18,960
Eli Bresler and Yvonne Mondragon

61
00:03:18,960 --> 00:03:21,090
and they will moderate today's discussion.

62
00:03:21,090 --> 00:03:24,720
Take it away!
(audience applauding)

63
00:03:24,720 --> 00:03:27,813
- [Yvonne] Thank you,
hello, can you hear me?

64
00:03:28,860 --> 00:03:31,560
So Blake, thank you for being here.

65
00:03:31,560 --> 00:03:34,170
As we've mentioned before here at Haas,

66
00:03:34,170 --> 00:03:37,170
we care a lot about social
impact and entrepreneurship,

67
00:03:37,170 --> 00:03:40,380
so everybody here is very
excited to hear from you.

68
00:03:40,380 --> 00:03:43,170
To start us off, why don't
you tell us a little bit

69
00:03:43,170 --> 00:03:45,240
about your journey starting Toms,

70
00:03:45,240 --> 00:03:47,490
kind of from your perspective,

71
00:03:47,490 --> 00:03:49,950
what influenced the one for one model

72
00:03:49,950 --> 00:03:52,630
and how that helped drive
the success of Toms?

73
00:03:52,630 --> 00:03:55,650
- [Blake] Okay, great, well
Toms started in Argentina

74
00:03:55,650 --> 00:03:59,610
and there's kind of a funny
backstory of how I got there.

75
00:03:59,610 --> 00:04:01,387
How many people have
seen the reality TV show,

76
00:04:01,387 --> 00:04:03,240
"The Amazing Race?"

77
00:04:03,240 --> 00:04:04,073
Oh, a lot of people.

78
00:04:04,073 --> 00:04:06,871
Okay, did anyone see it 20
years ago when I was on it?

79
00:04:06,871 --> 00:04:07,830
(audience laughing)

80
00:04:07,830 --> 00:04:09,303
Two people, yes!

81
00:04:10,560 --> 00:04:13,260
So my sister and I were on this
TV show, "The Amazing Race,"

82
00:04:13,260 --> 00:04:14,490
and for those who haven't seen it,

83
00:04:14,490 --> 00:04:16,770
you're racing around the world for 30 days

84
00:04:16,770 --> 00:04:19,410
and there's a million
dollar prize at the end.

85
00:04:19,410 --> 00:04:21,060
And interestingly enough,

86
00:04:21,060 --> 00:04:24,240
the last leg of the race
was here in San Francisco

87
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:29,240
and unfortunately at a very
critical moment, my sister said,

88
00:04:29,737 --> 00:04:32,220
"We're almost there to
win the million dollars.

89
00:04:32,220 --> 00:04:33,960
Let's stop and ask for directions

90
00:04:33,960 --> 00:04:35,580
to make sure we know where we're going."

91
00:04:35,580 --> 00:04:37,230
And as it's such a cliche,

92
00:04:37,230 --> 00:04:40,320
as a man, I said, "No, I
know exactly where I'm going.

93
00:04:40,320 --> 00:04:42,000
We don't need to stop and ask."

94
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:43,740
And next thing I know, we were lost

95
00:04:43,740 --> 00:04:46,655
and we lost the million
dollars by four minutes.

96
00:04:46,655 --> 00:04:47,488
(audience exclaiming)

97
00:04:47,488 --> 00:04:50,280
And after we lost a million
dollars by four minutes,

98
00:04:50,280 --> 00:04:52,980
about a month later, I got a
text message from my sister

99
00:04:52,980 --> 00:04:55,500
and it was this like
random string of numbers.

100
00:04:55,500 --> 00:04:56,400
And I thought, that's weird.

101
00:04:56,400 --> 00:04:57,775
And I thought, well,

102
00:04:57,775 --> 00:04:59,190
maybe she kind of
butt-dialed me or something

103
00:04:59,190 --> 00:05:00,810
and that's what came through on the text.

104
00:05:00,810 --> 00:05:02,460
So I didn't respond or anything.

105
00:05:02,460 --> 00:05:05,310
And then the next month I
got another text message

106
00:05:05,310 --> 00:05:06,960
and it's a different
random string of numbers.

107
00:05:06,960 --> 00:05:08,760
And so I called her and I said, "Paige,

108
00:05:08,760 --> 00:05:10,200
what's with these text messages?"

109
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:11,640
And she goes, "That's the interest you owe

110
00:05:11,640 --> 00:05:13,405
me on my half million dollars."

111
00:05:13,405 --> 00:05:14,760
(audience laughing)

112
00:05:14,760 --> 00:05:16,740
And so that was a great experience,

113
00:05:16,740 --> 00:05:18,060
but what, "The Amazing Race," did

114
00:05:18,060 --> 00:05:19,950
was it really took me
to all these countries

115
00:05:19,950 --> 00:05:22,980
I had never been to and
Argentina was one of them.

116
00:05:22,980 --> 00:05:24,960
And so I decided I wanted to go back

117
00:05:24,960 --> 00:05:25,860
to a lot of the countries

118
00:05:25,860 --> 00:05:30,660
and so in January of 2006,
I took a trip to Argentina.

119
00:05:30,660 --> 00:05:32,370
I was there for about a month

120
00:05:32,370 --> 00:05:35,220
and I experienced a bunch
of different things.

121
00:05:35,220 --> 00:05:37,620
And one of the things
that I experienced was,

122
00:05:37,620 --> 00:05:40,620
and it was the first time
that I'd really seen this,

123
00:05:40,620 --> 00:05:43,260
was just really intense poverty.

124
00:05:43,260 --> 00:05:47,160
Just outside of Bueno Aires
I saw many kids in the street

125
00:05:47,160 --> 00:05:50,220
and not wearing shoes and sniffing glue

126
00:05:50,220 --> 00:05:53,670
and just some really horrible
things with these children.

127
00:05:53,670 --> 00:05:55,530
And at the same time,

128
00:05:55,530 --> 00:05:57,510
I noticed that a lot of the young people

129
00:05:57,510 --> 00:06:01,080
were wearing these slip-on
shoes called alpargatas.

130
00:06:01,080 --> 00:06:03,570
And I grew up wearing Converse and Vans

131
00:06:03,570 --> 00:06:05,850
and kind of these thick bulkier, slip-ons,

132
00:06:05,850 --> 00:06:09,030
but these were like really different.

133
00:06:09,030 --> 00:06:11,730
And so I asked my friend at
the time about the shoes,

134
00:06:11,730 --> 00:06:13,560
and he said, "Yeah, the farmers wear them,

135
00:06:13,560 --> 00:06:15,240
the polo players wear them."

136
00:06:15,240 --> 00:06:17,670
And I thought they were
really interesting.

137
00:06:17,670 --> 00:06:19,470
In a very serendipitous way,

138
00:06:19,470 --> 00:06:21,720
I met a woman that was running a nonprofit

139
00:06:21,720 --> 00:06:24,060
and they were specifically helping kids

140
00:06:24,060 --> 00:06:26,160
get shoes for school.

141
00:06:26,160 --> 00:06:27,930
The shoes was part of the uniform

142
00:06:27,930 --> 00:06:30,120
and so many of these kids
that I saw in the streets,

143
00:06:30,120 --> 00:06:31,710
the reason they were in the
streets and not in school

144
00:06:31,710 --> 00:06:34,230
was 'cause their families
couldn't afford the uniform,

145
00:06:34,230 --> 00:06:35,700
which included a pair of shoes.

146
00:06:35,700 --> 00:06:37,890
And so, I had this kind of morning ritual

147
00:06:37,890 --> 00:06:38,850
where I drink my coffee

148
00:06:38,850 --> 00:06:40,290
and write in my journal about the day

149
00:06:40,290 --> 00:06:42,390
and have some of the
things I'm thinking about

150
00:06:42,390 --> 00:06:43,260
and goals for the day

151
00:06:43,260 --> 00:06:44,910
and when I was sitting on this farm

152
00:06:44,910 --> 00:06:46,333
that I was staying at in Argentina,

153
00:06:46,333 --> 00:06:47,760
I was writing in my journal

154
00:06:47,760 --> 00:06:50,670
and this idea came to me and
the idea was really simple.

155
00:06:50,670 --> 00:06:53,190
It was just, what if I took these shoes

156
00:06:53,190 --> 00:06:54,930
that I see all these people wearing

157
00:06:54,930 --> 00:06:55,980
that I've never seen before

158
00:06:55,980 --> 00:06:58,710
and sell them back in Venice,
California where I live

159
00:06:58,710 --> 00:07:00,660
and every time I sell a pair,

160
00:07:00,660 --> 00:07:03,210
we give a pair to these kids
that desperately need them

161
00:07:03,210 --> 00:07:05,370
for their school uniform

162
00:07:05,370 --> 00:07:08,820
and we'll call it shoes for tomorrow.

163
00:07:08,820 --> 00:07:10,740
The idea is that if you buy a pair today,

164
00:07:10,740 --> 00:07:12,210
we give a pair tomorrow

165
00:07:12,210 --> 00:07:14,796
and most people think my
name is Tom, it's not.

166
00:07:14,796 --> 00:07:15,629
(audience laughing)

167
00:07:15,629 --> 00:07:18,210
But that's where the name Toms came from

168
00:07:18,210 --> 00:07:20,070
was Tomorrow's Shoes.

169
00:07:20,070 --> 00:07:21,967
And we wanted to put the whole word,

170
00:07:21,967 --> 00:07:23,190
"Tomorrow's," on the tag,

171
00:07:23,190 --> 00:07:25,800
but it wouldn't fit, so
we shortened it to Tom's

172
00:07:25,800 --> 00:07:28,173
and that's how we got the name, yeah.

173
00:07:29,670 --> 00:07:30,503
- [Eli] That's really incredible

174
00:07:30,503 --> 00:07:32,910
and as someone with two
sisters in the crowd right now,

175
00:07:32,910 --> 00:07:33,780
I can only imagine

176
00:07:33,780 --> 00:07:36,420
that costing us all a million
dollars for four minutes,

177
00:07:36,420 --> 00:07:38,310
you're probably catching
grief about that today,

178
00:07:38,310 --> 00:07:41,280
so I empathize with that.

179
00:07:41,280 --> 00:07:43,680
we are on an NBA campus and
so I think one of the things

180
00:07:43,680 --> 00:07:46,110
that we're really curious
about is the business of Tom's

181
00:07:46,110 --> 00:07:48,630
and the one for one model signals a lot

182
00:07:48,630 --> 00:07:51,810
how you can have a profitable,
successful enterprise

183
00:07:51,810 --> 00:07:54,900
and also have it do good,
do well for the world.

184
00:07:54,900 --> 00:07:57,180
So I think one of the
things we're curious about

185
00:07:57,180 --> 00:07:59,400
is how you layer in social responsibility

186
00:07:59,400 --> 00:08:01,350
and what complexity that adds.

187
00:08:01,350 --> 00:08:03,000
what challenges have you faced

188
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:05,670
in maintaining Todd's
commitment to social impact

189
00:08:05,670 --> 00:08:08,460
while ensuring the company's
financial responsibility?

190
00:08:08,460 --> 00:08:10,230
What sacrifices do you have to make

191
00:08:10,230 --> 00:08:11,820
on both sides of that coin

192
00:08:11,820 --> 00:08:13,740
to make sure that both can succeed,

193
00:08:13,740 --> 00:08:15,783
financially and your social goals?

194
00:08:16,800 --> 00:08:19,800
- [Blake] Okay, well, I think maybe start

195
00:08:19,800 --> 00:08:20,730
in answering the question,

196
00:08:20,730 --> 00:08:22,920
just thinking about the financial aspects

197
00:08:22,920 --> 00:08:24,210
of the Tom's business model,

198
00:08:24,210 --> 00:08:25,908
there's really kind of a magic formula

199
00:08:25,908 --> 00:08:28,680
that Tom's, kind of created

200
00:08:28,680 --> 00:08:30,780
and that other businesses have followed

201
00:08:30,780 --> 00:08:33,810
and it's not necessarily
just the one for one model.

202
00:08:33,810 --> 00:08:36,210
It's this idea that our giving

203
00:08:36,210 --> 00:08:38,070
and our commitment to our impact

204
00:08:38,070 --> 00:08:41,250
had a greater influence on the customer

205
00:08:41,250 --> 00:08:43,710
than any type of marketing
we could ever do.

206
00:08:43,710 --> 00:08:47,790
And so, while many companies
might spend 10%, 15%, 20%

207
00:08:47,790 --> 00:08:51,330
of their margin on marketing,
we spent basically zero.

208
00:08:51,330 --> 00:08:53,580
And instead we took that money

209
00:08:53,580 --> 00:08:56,130
and we used it to pay for
another pair of shoes,

210
00:08:56,130 --> 00:08:58,830
which was oftentimes less
expensive than the marketing.

211
00:08:58,830 --> 00:09:02,700
And so that's why like when we
became extremely profitable,

212
00:09:02,700 --> 00:09:04,230
which was a kind of a surprise to me

213
00:09:04,230 --> 00:09:05,700
because when I started the,

214
00:09:05,700 --> 00:09:08,070
we didn't even call it a
business, we called it a project,

215
00:09:08,070 --> 00:09:09,750
we started the Tom's project,

216
00:09:09,750 --> 00:09:13,140
we priced the shoes based
on how much it cost for us

217
00:09:13,140 --> 00:09:15,780
to make them in a guy's
garage in Argentina.

218
00:09:15,780 --> 00:09:18,450
So you can imagine when
the business took off

219
00:09:18,450 --> 00:09:20,400
and all of a sudden we were
working at big factories,

220
00:09:20,400 --> 00:09:21,689
the cost went down so much

221
00:09:21,689 --> 00:09:24,780
that our profit went up a lot.

222
00:09:24,780 --> 00:09:27,731
And so, we really had to focus on,

223
00:09:27,731 --> 00:09:30,090
to be successful as a business,

224
00:09:30,090 --> 00:09:32,340
we actually need to focus on our giving

225
00:09:32,340 --> 00:09:33,510
as much as anything else

226
00:09:33,510 --> 00:09:35,400
and telling that story of the giving.

227
00:09:35,400 --> 00:09:37,740
And I really learned that lesson

228
00:09:37,740 --> 00:09:39,120
in a really kind of funny way.

229
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:43,710
I was in the JFK airport,
we had just started Toms

230
00:09:43,710 --> 00:09:46,200
and I was probably two, three months in

231
00:09:46,200 --> 00:09:48,690
and the only people we really sold Toms to

232
00:09:48,690 --> 00:09:53,690
was like my parents, their
friends, my neighbors

233
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,220
and I was living in Venice, California.

234
00:09:56,220 --> 00:09:58,950
And so, I was in New York
trying to get new stores

235
00:09:58,950 --> 00:10:02,490
and I decided to go for a run

236
00:10:02,490 --> 00:10:04,050
right before I had to get to my flight

237
00:10:04,050 --> 00:10:06,990
and so I went to the JFK
airport not wearing Tom's,

238
00:10:06,990 --> 00:10:09,810
which was unique for me, at
that point, I always wore Toms.

239
00:10:09,810 --> 00:10:11,217
And so I had my running shoes on

240
00:10:11,217 --> 00:10:13,530
and I go to the American
Airlines check-in counter,

241
00:10:13,530 --> 00:10:14,370
I'll never forget this,

242
00:10:14,370 --> 00:10:16,920
it was kinda one of the
most meaningful things

243
00:10:16,920 --> 00:10:18,300
the early days of Tom's for me,

244
00:10:18,300 --> 00:10:21,180
and I went to do the kind
of electronic check-in

245
00:10:21,180 --> 00:10:24,300
and next to me there was this woman

246
00:10:24,300 --> 00:10:26,190
wearing a red pair of Toms

247
00:10:26,190 --> 00:10:29,550
and I had never seen a
stranger wearing our shoes.

248
00:10:29,550 --> 00:10:32,670
I mean, it was so cool!
(audience laughing)

249
00:10:32,670 --> 00:10:33,900
It was such a cool moment

250
00:10:33,900 --> 00:10:36,180
and so I'm kind of looking at her

251
00:10:36,180 --> 00:10:38,280
and I'm thinking, gosh,
should I say something?

252
00:10:38,280 --> 00:10:41,310
And so I decide to say, "Hey,

253
00:10:41,310 --> 00:10:45,210
I really love these shoes
you're wearing, what are they?"

254
00:10:45,210 --> 00:10:49,050
And she says, "Tom's, Tom's Shoes."

255
00:10:49,050 --> 00:10:50,310
And so I'm doing the check-in.

256
00:10:50,310 --> 00:10:51,240
I'm like, "Oh, that's cool."

257
00:10:51,240 --> 00:10:53,400
And she literally physically
put her hand on me

258
00:10:53,400 --> 00:10:55,200
and said, "No, you don't understand!

259
00:10:55,200 --> 00:10:57,426
This is the most amazing
company in the world!"

260
00:10:57,426 --> 00:10:58,770
(audience laughing)

261
00:10:58,770 --> 00:11:01,320
She goes, "When I bought
this pair of shoes,

262
00:11:01,320 --> 00:11:04,110
they gave a pair to a child in Argentina

263
00:11:04,110 --> 00:11:05,580
and there's this guy who started,

264
00:11:05,580 --> 00:11:07,591
I heard he lives on a boat..."
(audience laughing)

265
00:11:07,591 --> 00:11:09,660
And she just went on and on.

266
00:11:09,660 --> 00:11:12,510
So I was feeling bad and so I
was like, I had to stop her.

267
00:11:12,510 --> 00:11:17,370
And I'm like, "Excuse me,
actually, I'm that guy.

268
00:11:17,370 --> 00:11:20,250
I am Blake, I live on a
boat and I started Tom's."

269
00:11:20,250 --> 00:11:22,200
And she goes to me, she looks at me like,

270
00:11:22,200 --> 00:11:25,650
like deer in headlights,
she's so, like, what?

271
00:11:25,650 --> 00:11:27,923
And she goes, "Why'd you cut your hair?"

272
00:11:27,923 --> 00:11:29,250
(audience laughing)

273
00:11:29,250 --> 00:11:32,250
And I was like, "How did
she know I cut my hair?"

274
00:11:32,250 --> 00:11:36,000
And I realized that she
wasn't just a customer,

275
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:38,820
she was just totally invested in this

276
00:11:38,820 --> 00:11:40,830
and she'd watched all
these videos on YouTube

277
00:11:40,830 --> 00:11:42,180
of us giving the shoes away.

278
00:11:42,180 --> 00:11:45,060
And so, that's how she
knew I had cut my hair.

279
00:11:45,060 --> 00:11:48,000
But then as I said thanks
to her and went to my flight

280
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:50,100
and started thinking
about that conversation,

281
00:11:50,100 --> 00:11:54,780
I realized that this woman
took the time out of her day

282
00:11:54,780 --> 00:11:57,630
at an airport to tell
a stranger about Toms.

283
00:11:57,630 --> 00:12:00,330
So how many people has she
already told about Toms?

284
00:12:00,330 --> 00:12:02,370
I mean, definitely all
her friends and family

285
00:12:02,370 --> 00:12:06,990
and people on Facebook and
so I realized that the effect

286
00:12:06,990 --> 00:12:10,230
of just one customer
connecting to our giving

287
00:12:10,230 --> 00:12:13,470
was gonna have such a magnitude effect

288
00:12:13,470 --> 00:12:15,900
on how many shoes we would
sell and ultimately give away.

289
00:12:15,900 --> 00:12:17,640
And so that's when we really decided

290
00:12:17,640 --> 00:12:19,170
that as a business model,

291
00:12:19,170 --> 00:12:21,600
we were not necessarily gonna be focused

292
00:12:21,600 --> 00:12:23,670
on the things that a
traditional business was,

293
00:12:23,670 --> 00:12:26,010
but really focused on
giving and telling our story

294
00:12:26,010 --> 00:12:27,993
and that's why our model works so well.

295
00:12:28,860 --> 00:12:31,321
- [Yvonne] Yeah, that's awesome to hear,

296
00:12:31,321 --> 00:12:34,290
to see that something you believe in,

297
00:12:34,290 --> 00:12:35,940
others also believe in

298
00:12:35,940 --> 00:12:39,930
and it grew into what Toms is today.

299
00:12:39,930 --> 00:12:41,519
Going off of that,

300
00:12:41,519 --> 00:12:45,510
large scale innovation is
something that is very hard to do.

301
00:12:45,510 --> 00:12:47,340
There's some products
out there that we see

302
00:12:47,340 --> 00:12:50,887
that we think this large
scale is inevitable.

303
00:12:50,887 --> 00:12:54,930
What are some of the
challenges that you experienced

304
00:12:54,930 --> 00:12:58,713
with scaling up Toms and how
did you face those challenges?

305
00:13:01,860 --> 00:13:02,820
- [Blake] Well, the biggest challenge

306
00:13:02,820 --> 00:13:05,190
was making the dang shoes.

307
00:13:05,190 --> 00:13:07,800
I mean, I had never made shoes before.

308
00:13:07,800 --> 00:13:10,680
My Argentine polo playing partner, Alejo,

309
00:13:10,680 --> 00:13:12,180
had never made shoes before

310
00:13:12,180 --> 00:13:13,170
and we met this guy

311
00:13:13,170 --> 00:13:15,750
who said he could make them in his garage,

312
00:13:15,750 --> 00:13:18,450
which he could do somewhat sufficiently.

313
00:13:18,450 --> 00:13:21,060
So really scaling the production

314
00:13:21,060 --> 00:13:23,610
once the business took off
was really, really hard.

315
00:13:24,720 --> 00:13:26,550
what I found was the key to that

316
00:13:26,550 --> 00:13:29,610
was finding people who
did know how to make shoes

317
00:13:29,610 --> 00:13:32,160
and had done it for
companies that really scaled.

318
00:13:32,160 --> 00:13:36,076
And so, we very early
on were able to attract

319
00:13:36,076 --> 00:13:39,540
a really senior executive from
one of the big shoe companies

320
00:13:39,540 --> 00:13:42,060
to come and start working
in my apartment with us.

321
00:13:42,060 --> 00:13:44,640
I think he was employee
number two or three

322
00:13:44,640 --> 00:13:46,983
and the first two were
interns off Craigslist.

323
00:13:48,097 --> 00:13:48,930
(audience laughing)

324
00:13:48,930 --> 00:13:52,890
But Sean came to us and I
remember it was really cool,

325
00:13:52,890 --> 00:13:55,800
I went on a factory tour with him in Asia

326
00:13:55,800 --> 00:13:58,320
and we were drinking beers one night

327
00:13:58,320 --> 00:13:59,910
and I said to him, I said, "Sean,

328
00:13:59,910 --> 00:14:02,340
you know, why did you come to Toms?"

329
00:14:02,340 --> 00:14:06,010
Because I mean, we're paying
you probably half as much

330
00:14:06,896 --> 00:14:11,370
as you as you made at this, I
think it was Nike or Converse,

331
00:14:11,370 --> 00:14:13,110
I forget where he was at before

332
00:14:13,110 --> 00:14:15,990
and he's very senior in his role,

333
00:14:15,990 --> 00:14:18,330
he'd worked in the industry
for I think 30 years.

334
00:14:18,330 --> 00:14:20,370
And I said, "'Cause we're paying

335
00:14:20,370 --> 00:14:23,310
you probably half or two
thirds what you're paying

336
00:14:23,310 --> 00:14:27,177
and you're having to do the
job of basically five people."

337
00:14:28,170 --> 00:14:30,477
And it was so cool, he's told me, he said,

338
00:14:30,477 --> 00:14:32,070
and this goes back to the giving

339
00:14:32,070 --> 00:14:33,930
being our key differentiator

340
00:14:33,930 --> 00:14:38,930
is he said, "Because now
my kids think I'm so cool

341
00:14:39,510 --> 00:14:42,120
and my daughter thinks it's so amazing

342
00:14:42,120 --> 00:14:44,280
that I'm helping kids get shoes.

343
00:14:44,280 --> 00:14:49,020
And so that's a big part of why I'm here."

344
00:14:49,020 --> 00:14:52,740
And that's also, I realized,
just focusing on our giving

345
00:14:52,740 --> 00:14:55,710
and staying authentic to
that was so important,

346
00:14:55,710 --> 00:14:56,640
because without Sean,

347
00:14:56,640 --> 00:14:59,523
we never would've been
able to scale the business.

348
00:15:01,110 --> 00:15:01,943
- [Eli] That's really interesting.

349
00:15:01,943 --> 00:15:03,990
It feels like people are attracted to it

350
00:15:03,990 --> 00:15:05,370
because it's solving two problems.

351
00:15:05,370 --> 00:15:07,200
It's putting stylish
shoes on people's feet,

352
00:15:07,200 --> 00:15:09,000
that's actually a fun problem to solve,

353
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:11,610
it's also putting shoes on
the feet of people in need

354
00:15:11,610 --> 00:15:13,860
and that's an even more
fun problem to solve.

355
00:15:13,860 --> 00:15:17,010
I think when we think about
the most successful businesses,

356
00:15:17,010 --> 00:15:18,060
the most successful products,

357
00:15:18,060 --> 00:15:19,560
like that's what they fundamentally do.

358
00:15:19,560 --> 00:15:22,200
They solve problems that
people can't solve themselves.

359
00:15:22,200 --> 00:15:25,770
Like, Velcro allows me to fasten my shoes,

360
00:15:25,770 --> 00:15:28,140
Advil allows me to reduce
pain, inflammation,

361
00:15:28,140 --> 00:15:29,310
all that kind of stuff.

362
00:15:29,310 --> 00:15:32,100
How do you go about figuring out

363
00:15:32,100 --> 00:15:34,860
what problems people need to solve

364
00:15:34,860 --> 00:15:37,050
and how you can solve that problem?

365
00:15:37,050 --> 00:15:38,760
And even one step further,

366
00:15:38,760 --> 00:15:40,650
if you know how to solve the problem,

367
00:15:40,650 --> 00:15:42,780
how do you turn that into a
business that can solve it

368
00:15:42,780 --> 00:15:43,920
for a lot of people?

369
00:15:43,920 --> 00:15:46,170
What does problem solving and filling need

370
00:15:46,170 --> 00:15:47,070
look like for you?

371
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:49,110
- [Blake] Okay, so I'm gonna tell a story

372
00:15:49,110 --> 00:15:51,180
from a different company.

373
00:15:51,180 --> 00:15:54,120
So I've started, I think
five or six companies

374
00:15:54,120 --> 00:15:56,370
and most of them were before Tom's

375
00:15:56,370 --> 00:16:00,120
and one of them was an online
driver's education company.

376
00:16:00,120 --> 00:16:02,070
Now, how I got into that business

377
00:16:02,070 --> 00:16:07,070
is really by listening
to someone's problem.

378
00:16:08,370 --> 00:16:10,860
I was at a barbecue for
a television network

379
00:16:10,860 --> 00:16:12,300
that I'd also helped start

380
00:16:12,300 --> 00:16:16,320
and my head of programming's son was there

381
00:16:16,320 --> 00:16:18,060
and he was 15 years old.

382
00:16:18,060 --> 00:16:20,340
And I asked him, "What are
you doing this summer?"

383
00:16:20,340 --> 00:16:23,430
And he kind of said, "Uh,
I'm learning to drive."

384
00:16:23,430 --> 00:16:25,410
And I was like, huh, I mean,

385
00:16:25,410 --> 00:16:26,970
I would think that if
you're learning to drive,

386
00:16:26,970 --> 00:16:28,590
that'd be exciting for a 15-year-old.

387
00:16:28,590 --> 00:16:30,960
And I said, "Well, why
is learning to drive

388
00:16:30,960 --> 00:16:31,830
not that exciting?"

389
00:16:31,830 --> 00:16:35,040
And he said, "Oh, I'm in this classroom

390
00:16:35,040 --> 00:16:38,370
and it's stinky and it's dark
and it's in this like mall

391
00:16:38,370 --> 00:16:40,440
and I got this old lady teacher

392
00:16:40,440 --> 00:16:42,840
and I can barely understand
what she's saying

393
00:16:42,840 --> 00:16:44,430
and the cars are just crap."

394
00:16:44,430 --> 00:16:46,860
And I mean, he was just super negative.

395
00:16:46,860 --> 00:16:48,900
And I was thinking, well, this is not good

396
00:16:48,900 --> 00:16:51,090
for our safety on our California highways.

397
00:16:51,090 --> 00:16:52,050
(audience laughing)

398
00:16:52,050 --> 00:16:55,890
If this is how engaged or
disengaged this kid is,

399
00:16:55,890 --> 00:16:57,780
like, we are in a lot of trouble.

400
00:16:57,780 --> 00:16:59,520
And so I went home that night,

401
00:16:59,520 --> 00:17:02,367
and this is right when MySpace was out

402
00:17:02,367 --> 00:17:04,151
and there was no Facebook yet

403
00:17:04,151 --> 00:17:06,540
and some of you probably don't even know

404
00:17:06,540 --> 00:17:08,103
what MySpace is, I'm realizing,

405
00:17:10,770 --> 00:17:12,540
and it was also when
they were just starting

406
00:17:12,540 --> 00:17:13,800
to do things online

407
00:17:13,800 --> 00:17:16,920
that traditionally had been
done in brick and mortar.

408
00:17:16,920 --> 00:17:21,060
And so I thought, well, one
way to solve this problem

409
00:17:21,060 --> 00:17:23,520
of these classrooms that are
really not that inspiring,

410
00:17:23,520 --> 00:17:26,250
they're usually in like
Sears malls or something,

411
00:17:26,250 --> 00:17:29,100
is to see if we could
take this class online.

412
00:17:29,100 --> 00:17:32,250
And so that could be more
engaging, more entertaining,

413
00:17:32,250 --> 00:17:34,260
they could do it at their own pace.

414
00:17:34,260 --> 00:17:36,210
And so that was one idea

415
00:17:36,210 --> 00:17:38,910
and I worked really hard
with some legislature

416
00:17:38,910 --> 00:17:42,540
to get that changed in California
so that we could do that.

417
00:17:42,540 --> 00:17:43,830
And so, that was step one.

418
00:17:43,830 --> 00:17:47,760
And step two was, we
gotta get better cars,

419
00:17:47,760 --> 00:17:50,430
like these cars have
gotta be more interesting.

420
00:17:50,430 --> 00:17:53,490
Now, this was right when
Toyota came out with a Prius

421
00:17:53,490 --> 00:17:55,680
and so they had this huge desire

422
00:17:55,680 --> 00:17:58,830
to get people to know what
an electric car even was.

423
00:17:58,830 --> 00:18:00,810
And starting with young people

424
00:18:00,810 --> 00:18:03,150
who might be more environmentally inclined

425
00:18:03,150 --> 00:18:04,560
was a big part of their thing

426
00:18:04,560 --> 00:18:07,560
and so I cold-called
Toyota down in Torrance

427
00:18:07,560 --> 00:18:11,040
and got a meeting and they
decided to give us four cars

428
00:18:11,040 --> 00:18:13,440
at like, basically at the cost.

429
00:18:13,440 --> 00:18:15,720
But the third thing was the teacher

430
00:18:15,720 --> 00:18:17,013
and that was something

431
00:18:17,013 --> 00:18:18,150
that was gonna be a
little bit harder to do,

432
00:18:18,150 --> 00:18:20,610
because people who were
kind of driver's ed teachers

433
00:18:20,610 --> 00:18:22,470
were pretty, a very specific type.

434
00:18:22,470 --> 00:18:26,840
They're usually retired,
they were usually...

435
00:18:29,797 --> 00:18:31,260
I mean, I think everyone can remember

436
00:18:31,260 --> 00:18:32,490
the driver's ed teacher.
(audience laughing)

437
00:18:32,490 --> 00:18:33,810
unless you went to our school,

438
00:18:33,810 --> 00:18:35,601
'cause I'll tell you why ours was special

439
00:18:35,601 --> 00:18:37,350
and you'd really remember,

440
00:18:37,350 --> 00:18:38,850
because what we decided

441
00:18:38,850 --> 00:18:41,610
was these teenagers were
not paying attention

442
00:18:41,610 --> 00:18:42,870
to their teachers at all.

443
00:18:42,870 --> 00:18:43,703
And so we thought about,

444
00:18:43,703 --> 00:18:45,810
okay, how can we get
them to pay attention?

445
00:18:45,810 --> 00:18:47,610
Now we were lucky, 'cause
we lived in Los Angeles,

446
00:18:47,610 --> 00:18:49,903
so we had a lot of actors and models.

447
00:18:49,903 --> 00:18:50,736
(audience laughing)

448
00:18:50,736 --> 00:18:53,010
And so, we went and basically and hired

449
00:18:53,010 --> 00:18:55,140
a bunch of Abercrombie and Fitch models

450
00:18:55,140 --> 00:18:58,050
and actors that had all this free time

451
00:18:58,050 --> 00:19:00,000
and we knew that teenagers
pay attention to them

452
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:00,833
and it worked.

453
00:19:00,833 --> 00:19:03,840
And so we had them as our driver teachers

454
00:19:03,840 --> 00:19:06,360
and they would post pictures on MySpace

455
00:19:06,360 --> 00:19:08,059
of them and their teacher

456
00:19:08,059 --> 00:19:11,259
and so we solved all
three problems at once!

457
00:19:11,259 --> 00:19:12,480
(audience laughing)

458
00:19:12,480 --> 00:19:14,490
- [Eli] That's beautiful.

459
00:19:14,490 --> 00:19:16,890
I distinctly remember
my driver's ed teacher

460
00:19:16,890 --> 00:19:18,780
self branded himself as Tupac Dave

461
00:19:18,780 --> 00:19:20,580
and he was far too old to be trying

462
00:19:20,580 --> 00:19:22,260
to educate 15 year olds about Tupac

463
00:19:22,260 --> 00:19:23,669
and not teaching them about driving.

464
00:19:23,669 --> 00:19:24,672
(audience laughing)

465
00:19:24,672 --> 00:19:25,590
So I understand not learning anything

466
00:19:25,590 --> 00:19:26,610
and also trying to make sure

467
00:19:26,610 --> 00:19:28,910
kids actually learn how
to drive so it's safe.

468
00:19:30,300 --> 00:19:31,170
Pivoting a little bit,

469
00:19:31,170 --> 00:19:32,820
you're mentioning a lot of partnerships,

470
00:19:32,820 --> 00:19:33,960
like you're talking about Toyota,

471
00:19:33,960 --> 00:19:35,460
you're talking about these
Abercrombie and Fitch models,

472
00:19:35,460 --> 00:19:37,740
you've been talking about
this person that you met,

473
00:19:37,740 --> 00:19:39,660
who was working at Nike
came to work for you

474
00:19:39,660 --> 00:19:41,160
and I think partnerships are key

475
00:19:41,160 --> 00:19:42,840
and I know you often
talk about collaboration

476
00:19:42,840 --> 00:19:44,430
as being key to success.

477
00:19:44,430 --> 00:19:46,410
I'm curious, what are the green flags

478
00:19:46,410 --> 00:19:49,770
that you look for in
individuals, entities, partners

479
00:19:49,770 --> 00:19:52,560
of what you think would make
them a trustworthy partner,

480
00:19:52,560 --> 00:19:53,520
a good faith partner,

481
00:19:53,520 --> 00:19:55,050
someone who you wanna do business with,

482
00:19:55,050 --> 00:19:57,180
whether it's an individual or an entity,

483
00:19:57,180 --> 00:19:58,230
kind of what's your criteria?

484
00:19:58,230 --> 00:19:59,760
What are the green flags?

485
00:19:59,760 --> 00:20:01,320
- [Blake] I mean, I think
the most important thing

486
00:20:01,320 --> 00:20:04,620
in a partnership is, is the
partnership gonna be seen

487
00:20:04,620 --> 00:20:07,143
as something that's
authentic, that makes sense?

488
00:20:09,420 --> 00:20:12,870
The best partnership we
ever had was with AT&T

489
00:20:12,870 --> 00:20:16,320
It was truly one of the
biggest turning points

490
00:20:16,320 --> 00:20:18,960
in our business and I
would even say in my life,

491
00:20:18,960 --> 00:20:23,520
because what happened was, I
was on CNN doing an interview

492
00:20:23,520 --> 00:20:26,970
and I did an interview
and they were asking about

493
00:20:26,970 --> 00:20:28,710
how many people worked at
our company at this point,

494
00:20:28,710 --> 00:20:30,480
there were like 40 of us

495
00:20:30,480 --> 00:20:31,650
and we were selling all over the world.

496
00:20:31,650 --> 00:20:32,760
And they were like, "How in the world

497
00:20:32,760 --> 00:20:34,140
do you run your business,

498
00:20:34,140 --> 00:20:36,570
when you're in places
like Ethiopia giving shoes

499
00:20:36,570 --> 00:20:38,340
or Cambodia or Guatemala

500
00:20:38,340 --> 00:20:39,810
and there's only 40 of you

501
00:20:39,810 --> 00:20:42,090
and you're competing against
these big shoe companies?"

502
00:20:42,090 --> 00:20:43,320
And I pulled out my,

503
00:20:43,320 --> 00:20:44,870
it was funny, I had a
Blackberry back then.

504
00:20:44,870 --> 00:20:46,710
Do you guys remember Blackberry?

505
00:20:46,710 --> 00:20:48,780
Okay, good!
(audience murmuring)

506
00:20:48,780 --> 00:20:51,150
I'm not as old as I think!
(audience laughing)

507
00:20:51,150 --> 00:20:55,200
And so I pulled out my
Blackberry on the CNN interview

508
