00:40:21,607 --> 00:40:23,865
"Toms was a pioneering business model

974
00:40:23,865 --> 00:40:25,140
and I think received

975
00:40:25,140 --> 00:40:28,230
disproportionate scrutiny and criticism.

976
00:40:28,230 --> 00:40:29,640
How did you navigate it

977
00:40:29,640 --> 00:40:32,070
and what would you have done
differently in hindsight?"

978
00:40:32,070 --> 00:40:34,440
- [Blake] Hmm, yeah, I mean
that was a really hard thing

979
00:40:34,440 --> 00:40:38,970
for me because, hey, you hear this adage

980
00:40:38,970 --> 00:40:40,650
that the media loves to build you up

981
00:40:40,650 --> 00:40:42,360
so then they can kind of tear you down.

982
00:40:42,360 --> 00:40:47,360
And we got a lot of flack for
what impact were we having

983
00:40:48,630 --> 00:40:52,140
on communities by just going
out and offering a handout?

984
00:40:52,140 --> 00:40:53,430
And that was really hard,

985
00:40:53,430 --> 00:40:55,260
because all we were
trying to do is do good.

986
00:40:55,260 --> 00:40:56,640
I mean, I was in Argentina,

987
00:40:56,640 --> 00:40:58,980
saw kids that didn't have shoes,
wanted to give them shoes.

988
00:40:58,980 --> 00:41:02,470
Like I didn't come with a
public health background

989
00:41:04,170 --> 00:41:08,520
and so we really at first were like, angry

990
00:41:08,520 --> 00:41:11,190
and frustrated and scared by this

991
00:41:11,190 --> 00:41:12,990
and then we decided we
had to lean into it.

992
00:41:12,990 --> 00:41:15,660
And so ultimately what we
did was we hired some people

993
00:41:15,660 --> 00:41:16,920
who did have that background,

994
00:41:16,920 --> 00:41:20,550
who really understood the
impact of giving free goods

995
00:41:20,550 --> 00:41:23,760
in these communities, how it
impacted the local community

996
00:41:23,760 --> 00:41:27,090
and that really led us to
doing some local manufacturing.

997
00:41:27,090 --> 00:41:29,700
So we did a manufacturing plant in Haiti

998
00:41:29,700 --> 00:41:33,000
after the earthquake, which
was really successful.

999
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:36,390
We moved manufacturing also to Ethiopia,

1000
00:41:36,390 --> 00:41:38,880
which created a lot of jobs in Ethiopia.

1001
00:41:38,880 --> 00:41:40,110
And then the other thing we did

1002
00:41:40,110 --> 00:41:43,590
is we realized that just
giving shoes was not enough,

1003
00:41:43,590 --> 00:41:46,350
that we had to be part of
health programs as well.

1004
00:41:46,350 --> 00:41:48,060
And so there's a lot of health programs

1005
00:41:48,060 --> 00:41:51,510
for worms that kids get in
Central and South America

1006
00:41:51,510 --> 00:41:54,150
and so they want them to
come in and take the medicine

1007
00:41:54,150 --> 00:41:56,040
that would keep them from getting worms.

1008
00:41:56,040 --> 00:41:58,830
But the incentive, a lot of
kids wouldn't come do it,

1009
00:41:58,830 --> 00:42:00,000
they started saying, "If you come,

1010
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:01,320
you get a free pair of shoes."

1011
00:42:01,320 --> 00:42:03,030
And so that was a big incentive,

1012
00:42:03,030 --> 00:42:05,550
we worked with the Gates
Foundation on that.

1013
00:42:05,550 --> 00:42:07,950
And so yeah, so we just had
to get smarter and better

1014
00:42:07,950 --> 00:42:10,950
and more sophisticated
in how we did our giving.

1015
00:42:10,950 --> 00:42:13,020
- [Nora] Great, thanks.

1016
00:42:13,020 --> 00:42:15,030
So, "How have your previous ventures,

1017
00:42:15,030 --> 00:42:17,391
you mentioned four or five before Toms,

1018
00:42:17,391 --> 00:42:20,520
allowed you to be successful
as an entrepreneur?

1019
00:42:20,520 --> 00:42:22,920
What did you bring forward from those?"

1020
00:42:22,920 --> 00:42:24,720
- I mean, just lots of learning.

1021
00:42:24,720 --> 00:42:26,550
A couple of them were
moderately successful

1022
00:42:26,550 --> 00:42:28,854
and a couple of them were huge disasters.

1023
00:42:28,854 --> 00:42:30,870
(all laughing)

1024
00:42:30,870 --> 00:42:33,840
One disaster was after what I
was on, it was not a disaster,

1025
00:42:33,840 --> 00:42:35,703
but it was a failed business I guess,

1026
00:42:37,456 --> 00:42:40,290
is after I was on, "The
Amazing Race," I recognized

1027
00:42:40,290 --> 00:42:42,150
that there was this
tremendous amount of interest

1028
00:42:42,150 --> 00:42:46,200
in reality stars and
their 15 minutes of fame,

1029
00:42:46,200 --> 00:42:47,790
but there wasn't really a market

1030
00:42:47,790 --> 00:42:50,490
for really kind of capitalizing on that.

1031
00:42:50,490 --> 00:42:53,700
And so I decided to start at,

1032
00:42:53,700 --> 00:42:56,520
I think at the age of
25, I was very naive,

1033
00:42:56,520 --> 00:42:58,800
I decided to start a television network

1034
00:42:58,800 --> 00:43:01,110
and it was an all reality cable channel

1035
00:43:01,110 --> 00:43:02,190
in which I went around

1036
00:43:02,190 --> 00:43:05,040
and bought the rerun
rights of reality shows,

1037
00:43:05,040 --> 00:43:06,750
because once you kind of knew who won,

1038
00:43:06,750 --> 00:43:09,090
they really had no
interest at the networks.

1039
00:43:09,090 --> 00:43:10,920
But what I realized is
people cared so much

1040
00:43:10,920 --> 00:43:12,480
about the reality stars

1041
00:43:12,480 --> 00:43:14,250
that you could pair the
stars with the shows

1042
00:43:14,250 --> 00:43:16,320
and they could kind of
almost do like these shows

1043
00:43:16,320 --> 00:43:18,480
where they gave commentary
about what they were thinking

1044
00:43:18,480 --> 00:43:20,640
when they did that move on, "Survivor,"

1045
00:43:20,640 --> 00:43:23,250
or how they got that person
outed on, "Big Brother,"

1046
00:43:23,250 --> 00:43:24,420
or something like that.

1047
00:43:24,420 --> 00:43:26,370
And so we were able to get the content

1048
00:43:26,370 --> 00:43:28,230
for basically next to nothing,

1049
00:43:28,230 --> 00:43:30,300
but we knew that advertisers really wanted

1050
00:43:30,300 --> 00:43:33,180
to reach this audience, it was
mainly an 18 to 34 audience,

1051
00:43:33,180 --> 00:43:35,700
which was the key audience that
advertisers wanted to reach.

1052
00:43:35,700 --> 00:43:37,710
All these components showed

1053
00:43:37,710 --> 00:43:41,220
that we were gonna have incredible
success in this business.

1054
00:43:41,220 --> 00:43:43,257
The one thing we did not think about,

1055
00:43:43,257 --> 00:43:46,050
which was the most important
and the reason it failed,

1056
00:43:46,050 --> 00:43:49,310
was there were only
about 10 cable operators

1057
00:43:49,310 --> 00:43:51,150
in our country at that time

1058
00:43:51,150 --> 00:43:53,910
and including DirecTV, satellite provider.

1059
00:43:53,910 --> 00:43:55,710
And so the cable operators

1060
00:43:55,710 --> 00:43:57,750
and then DirecTV basically had a monopoly

1061
00:43:57,750 --> 00:43:59,400
as to what content we see.

1062
00:43:59,400 --> 00:44:02,220
It's not like today where
you can see it on Hulu

1063
00:44:02,220 --> 00:44:03,053
or you can see it

1064
00:44:03,053 --> 00:44:05,737
on a number of different
streaming networks,

1065
00:44:05,737 --> 00:44:09,063
obviously YouTube being one
of the dominant players.

1066
00:44:10,080 --> 00:44:13,438
So we basically had an amazing product,

1067
00:44:13,438 --> 00:44:14,910
people wanted it

1068
00:44:14,910 --> 00:44:17,190
and we had advertisers
willing to pay for it,

1069
00:44:17,190 --> 00:44:19,650
but our only way we were gonna
get anyone to ever see it

1070
00:44:19,650 --> 00:44:20,970
was through these cable operators.

1071
00:44:20,970 --> 00:44:23,550
And they had no need for another network.

1072
00:44:23,550 --> 00:44:26,280
I mean, they had 400 channels already,

1073
00:44:26,280 --> 00:44:28,740
getting one more was not gonna have anyone

1074
00:44:28,740 --> 00:44:31,140
all of a sudden decide to
pay for cable television.

1075
00:44:31,140 --> 00:44:32,430
They were paying for cable television

1076
00:44:32,430 --> 00:44:34,230
for many other reasons already.

1077
00:44:34,230 --> 00:44:37,470
And so they basically said,
"No, we're not interested."

1078
00:44:37,470 --> 00:44:40,500
And so, we ended up going outta business.

1079
00:44:40,500 --> 00:44:41,580
It was incredibly painful,

1080
00:44:41,580 --> 00:44:44,133
I had to lay off like 40 people,

1081
00:44:44,133 --> 00:44:48,180
it was a really challenging,
challenging situation.

1082
00:44:48,180 --> 00:44:50,070
And what I learned from that was,

1083
00:44:50,070 --> 00:44:52,680
is I never wanted to
be in a business again

1084
00:44:52,680 --> 00:44:55,500
where so few people had the power

1085
00:44:55,500 --> 00:44:57,360
to make it work or not work.

1086
00:44:57,360 --> 00:44:59,160
And so when I started Tom's,

1087
00:44:59,160 --> 00:45:03,390
the great thing was is
there's thousands of stores

1088
00:45:03,390 --> 00:45:05,220
in America that sell shoes

1089
00:45:05,220 --> 00:45:08,640
and so, I didn't have to go out

1090
00:45:08,640 --> 00:45:11,790
and get this one big fish customer,

1091
00:45:11,790 --> 00:45:14,100
I could go and focus on one after another,

1092
00:45:14,100 --> 00:45:15,390
after another, after another.

1093
00:45:15,390 --> 00:45:18,453
And so, that was one of the
real lessons that I learned

1094
00:45:18,453 --> 00:45:21,543
from an earlier business that failed,

1095
00:45:21,543 --> 00:45:24,720
that really helped me
as I thought about Toms.

1096
00:45:24,720 --> 00:45:25,950
- [Nora] Great, thank you.

1097
00:45:25,950 --> 00:45:29,370
So, "The buy one give
one model used by Toms

1098
00:45:29,370 --> 00:45:32,010
has longstanding been
a point of celebration,

1099
00:45:32,010 --> 00:45:34,560
however, there have been
shortcomings and challenges

1100
00:45:34,560 --> 00:45:35,640
and all of that.

1101
00:45:35,640 --> 00:45:36,630
Here's the big question,

1102
00:45:36,630 --> 00:45:41,160
Is it truly possible to
be a business for good?

1103
00:45:41,160 --> 00:45:44,850
And how should incoming
business leaders incorporate,"

1104
00:45:44,850 --> 00:45:46,057
I'll read it as it says,

1105
00:45:46,057 --> 00:45:49,587
"Corporate philanthropy
into their company brands?"

1106
00:45:51,600 --> 00:45:54,137
- Absolutely, my mic, hello?

1107
00:45:56,500 --> 00:45:59,640
I can just talk loud too.
(audience laughing)

1108
00:45:59,640 --> 00:46:02,190
- [Nora] We're trying to
broadcast though, hold on.

1109
00:46:03,377 --> 00:46:05,136
- [Blake] I could juggle.
(audience laughing)

1110
00:46:05,136 --> 00:46:08,512
- Hello, great, I don't
know how to juggle.

1111
00:46:08,512 --> 00:46:10,929
I would love to learn though.

1112
00:46:12,030 --> 00:46:15,253
So yeah, I mean I think that
there's a lot of examples

1113
00:46:15,253 --> 00:46:18,480
of businesses for good out there now,

1114
00:46:18,480 --> 00:46:20,610
Tom's being one of them.

1115
00:46:20,610 --> 00:46:24,300
I think the key is to really
focus on kind of three things

1116
00:46:24,300 --> 00:46:26,730
and you hear this a lot of
time in conscious capitalism,

1117
00:46:26,730 --> 00:46:30,331
the three, Ps, people,
planet and the profit.

1118
00:46:30,331 --> 00:46:33,420
By doing that you can
really build a business

1119
00:46:33,420 --> 00:46:36,723
where all those stakeholders
are equally benefiting.

1120
00:46:38,010 --> 00:46:41,253
I think, I will say the
bad news in all this is,

1121
00:46:41,253 --> 00:46:44,430
is that, and because
of the success of Toms

1122
00:46:44,430 --> 00:46:46,230
and other companies like Toms,

1123
00:46:46,230 --> 00:46:49,290
it's not as novel to
be a business for good

1124
00:46:49,290 --> 00:46:50,400
as it was when we started.

1125
00:46:50,400 --> 00:46:52,380
When we started, there
was nothing like this.

1126
00:46:52,380 --> 00:46:55,458
I mean there was Ben and
Jerry's that had been giving,

1127
00:46:55,458 --> 00:46:57,150
there was the Body Shop

1128
00:46:57,150 --> 00:46:59,010
that had been giving, Anita Roddick,

1129
00:46:59,010 --> 00:47:01,530
but neither of them built
their whole business on it

1130
00:47:01,530 --> 00:47:02,363
like we did with Tom's.

1131
00:47:02,363 --> 00:47:05,820
And so, we really kind of pioneered this

1132
00:47:05,820 --> 00:47:08,070
and several other businesses as well.

1133
00:47:08,070 --> 00:47:10,170
But now, today, if you
were starting a business,

1134
00:47:10,170 --> 00:47:12,360
I was talking to an
entrepreneur the other day

1135
00:47:12,360 --> 00:47:13,500
and they were saying, "Okay,

1136
00:47:13,500 --> 00:47:15,810
well we're gonna incorporate
this giving model,

1137
00:47:15,810 --> 00:47:18,090
helping people get
clean water, et cetera."

1138
00:47:18,090 --> 00:47:20,490
And they're gonna invest
a lot of money in that.

1139
00:47:20,490 --> 00:47:22,200
And I said to them, and
they thought it was weird

1140
00:47:22,200 --> 00:47:24,420
coming from me, I said, "I
don't think you should do that."

1141
00:47:24,420 --> 00:47:27,270
I was like, "I don't think
there's gonna be enough return

1142
00:47:27,270 --> 00:47:30,390
on your social investment to make it work,

1143
00:47:30,390 --> 00:47:32,130
like I talked about from
a marketing perspective,

1144
00:47:32,130 --> 00:47:34,110
because so many other companies
are already doing it."

1145
00:47:34,110 --> 00:47:36,840
So I think now what I
would say for entrepreneurs

1146
00:47:36,840 --> 00:47:39,060
that really want to do
good in business is,

1147
00:47:39,060 --> 00:47:40,650
it's really important to incorporate it

1148
00:47:40,650 --> 00:47:42,570
into the business model itself.

1149
00:47:42,570 --> 00:47:47,310
So to do it as an add-on or
if you do this, we give this,

1150
00:47:47,310 --> 00:47:49,320
I think can be more difficult,

1151
00:47:49,320 --> 00:47:52,170
but if the actual business itself,

1152
00:47:52,170 --> 00:47:54,270
and that's why I use the
example of green energy,

1153
00:47:54,270 --> 00:47:55,560
if the business itself

1154
00:47:55,560 --> 00:47:58,290
is making the planet a
more sustainable place,

1155
00:47:58,290 --> 00:48:00,150
then it is a business that's doing good,

1156
00:48:00,150 --> 00:48:02,670
but it's also not necessarily
having to carve out

1157
00:48:02,670 --> 00:48:05,940
a percentage of its margin to do so.

1158
00:48:05,940 --> 00:48:09,090
- [Nora] Okay and the final
question from the group

1159
00:48:09,090 --> 00:48:13,380
is, "You talk a lot about
conscious capitalism

1160
00:48:13,380 --> 00:48:17,850
and for-profit business and
in your book you also herald

1161
00:48:17,850 --> 00:48:20,700
or celebrate nonprofits
and philanthropists

1162
00:48:20,700 --> 00:48:24,060
and many people draw divisions
between those, but you don't.

1163
00:48:24,060 --> 00:48:25,260
Can you talk a little bit

1164
00:48:25,260 --> 00:48:27,930
about why you don't or how you see that?"

1165
00:48:27,930 --> 00:48:30,210
- [Blake] Well, what I tried
to do when I wrote this book,

1166
00:48:30,210 --> 00:48:33,413
which is a long time ago now,
as I'm thinking about it,

1167
00:48:33,413 --> 00:48:36,093
and I'm trying to remember
some of the things that I said,

1168
00:48:36,093 --> 00:48:37,895
(audience laughing)

1169
00:48:37,895 --> 00:48:42,895
but I tried to really highlight
two different organizations,

1170
00:48:45,720 --> 00:48:47,940
businesses that were innovative

1171
00:48:47,940 --> 00:48:51,120
and they're giving and
doing good like Tom's,

1172
00:48:51,120 --> 00:48:54,150
but then also some of these new nonprofits

1173
00:48:54,150 --> 00:48:55,140
that were being created

1174
00:48:55,140 --> 00:48:57,090
that were operating more like businesses.

1175
00:48:57,090 --> 00:48:59,310
And so I'll use Charity
Water is a great example.

1176
00:48:59,310 --> 00:49:00,420
How many people know Charity Water?

1177
00:49:00,420 --> 00:49:01,500
Raise your hand.

1178
00:49:01,500 --> 00:49:03,780
Oh wow, okay, you should
definitely check out Charity Water.

1179
00:49:03,780 --> 00:49:05,520
Not a lot of people here know.

1180
00:49:05,520 --> 00:49:06,990
but they've been incredibly innovative.

1181
00:49:06,990 --> 00:49:08,490
My friend Scott Harrison started it

1182
00:49:08,490 --> 00:49:10,020
the same year I started Tom's

1183
00:49:10,020 --> 00:49:13,170
and his idea was to bring
water to as many people

1184
00:49:13,170 --> 00:49:15,390
in the world that need it as possible.

1185
00:49:15,390 --> 00:49:18,552
And if you look at the
marketing of Charity Water,

1186
00:49:18,552 --> 00:49:21,510
it's as innovative and as slick

1187
00:49:21,510 --> 00:49:25,140
as any new Silicon Valley
backed tech startup.

1188
00:49:25,140 --> 00:49:27,090
I mean the branding is unbelievable.

1189
00:49:27,090 --> 00:49:29,640
The storytelling is unbelievable.

1190
00:49:29,640 --> 00:49:32,430
It competes with any business
in terms of marketing,

1191
00:49:32,430 --> 00:49:34,170
but it's a non-profit.

1192
00:49:34,170 --> 00:49:37,050
They also do really, really
innovative marketing campaigns

1193
00:49:37,050 --> 00:49:40,350
like asking people,
especially young people,

1194
00:49:40,350 --> 00:49:43,200
people who are 15, 16, 17 years old

1195
00:49:43,200 --> 00:49:48,150
to give up their birthday in
order to raise money for wells.

1196
00:49:48,150 --> 00:49:50,820
And they found this to
be incredibly successful,

1197
00:49:50,820 --> 00:49:52,320
especially with social media,

1198
00:49:52,320 --> 00:49:53,910
'cause they can message
out to all their friends,

1199
00:49:53,910 --> 00:49:55,950
like, "This year instead of having a party

1200
00:49:55,950 --> 00:49:58,915
or bringing a present, I'm
asking you to donate $10

1201
00:49:58,915 --> 00:50:01,890
for every year I've
been born or whatever."

1202
00:50:01,890 --> 00:50:03,270
And they've raised,

1203
00:50:03,270 --> 00:50:05,870
I mean literally they've
raised I think $300 million

1204
00:50:05,870 --> 00:50:09,210
in the last couple years
through these campaigns.

1205
00:50:09,210 --> 00:50:11,270
So I also try to talk
about something like that

1206
00:50:11,270 --> 00:50:12,780
in the book as well.

1207
00:50:12,780 --> 00:50:14,790
'Cause I think at the end of the day,

1208
00:50:14,790 --> 00:50:16,350
there's a lot of big problems in the world

1209
00:50:16,350 --> 00:50:18,131
that we wanna solve

1210
00:50:18,131 --> 00:50:21,330
and sometimes the right
vehicle is a non-profit,

1211
00:50:21,330 --> 00:50:23,677
like in the psychedelic space for instance

1212
00:50:23,677 --> 00:50:26,760
and then sometimes it is
a for-profit like Tom's.

1213
00:50:26,760 --> 00:50:29,091
And so I don't really see a
distinction between either,

1214
00:50:29,091 --> 00:50:31,320
as long as the organization is being used

1215
00:50:31,320 --> 00:50:33,420
to address a major problem in the world.

1216
00:50:33,420 --> 00:50:34,950
- [Nora] Great, thank you Blake.

1217
00:50:34,950 --> 00:50:35,880
We're hitting our time

1218
00:50:35,880 --> 00:50:37,590
and I'm gonna take a
little editorial freedom

1219
00:50:37,590 --> 00:50:38,823
and go off script here.

1220
00:50:39,660 --> 00:50:41,891
Alan Ross, would you come up here?

1221
00:50:41,891 --> 00:50:45,330
(audience applauding)

1222
00:50:45,330 --> 00:50:47,370
Alan does not know I
was calling him up here,

1223
00:50:47,370 --> 00:50:48,723
so bear with us.

1224
00:50:49,740 --> 00:50:52,980
Alan is doing something I
think is very innovative,

1225
00:50:52,980 --> 00:50:54,450
as a philanthropist

1226
00:50:54,450 --> 00:50:57,420
and he sent out an email just
yesterday asking us to vote.

1227
00:50:57,420 --> 00:51:00,690
So Alan, I wanna relinquish
the final two minutes to you

1228
00:51:00,690 --> 00:51:02,140
to make a pitch to the group.

1229
00:51:03,411 --> 00:51:04,590
- [Allan] Well thank you
so much, that's very sweet.

1230
00:51:04,590 --> 00:51:07,963
It's very surprising.
(all laughing)

1231
00:51:09,330 --> 00:51:11,040
I started something a couple years ago

1232
00:51:11,040 --> 00:51:15,090
called the Chris Kindness Award
and everyone calls me Chris,

1233
00:51:15,090 --> 00:51:16,740
I'm Alan.
(audience laughing)

1234
00:51:16,740 --> 00:51:20,340
I named it after my kids'
preschool teacher who died,

1235
00:51:20,340 --> 00:51:22,440
just the sweetest guy I ever met

1236
00:51:22,440 --> 00:51:24,480
and I give a thousand dollars every month

1237
00:51:24,480 --> 00:51:27,300
to someone in Berkeley
who does a kind act,

1238
00:51:27,300 --> 00:51:28,770
random acts of kindness.

1239
00:51:28,770 --> 00:51:31,050
We've had a gas station attendant,

1240
00:51:31,050 --> 00:51:35,109
someone who volunteers,
Children's Hospital, a teacher,

1241
00:51:35,109 --> 00:51:38,400
this month was a
16-year-old at Berkeley High

1242
00:51:38,400 --> 00:51:42,810
who's from Afghanistan, just
arrived in America a year ago,

1243
00:51:42,810 --> 00:51:46,770
who helps newcoming kids
from all over the world

1244
00:51:46,770 --> 00:51:48,540
acclimate to Berkeley High,

1245
00:51:48,540 --> 00:51:49,830
sweet, sweet stories

1246
00:51:49,830 --> 00:51:52,470
and we just announced our three finalists

1247
00:51:52,470 --> 00:51:55,140
for this month on Monday,

1248
00:51:55,140 --> 00:51:57,900
one of whom is a Haas person,

1249
00:51:57,900 --> 00:52:01,470
former student of mine of
20 years ago, Olive Davis.

1250
00:52:01,470 --> 00:52:04,140
Anyone know Olive?
(audience applauding)

1251
00:52:04,140 --> 00:52:07,260
Wonderful woman who was
with YA for a while,

1252
00:52:07,260 --> 00:52:08,760
Young Entrepreneurs at Haas,

1253
00:52:08,760 --> 00:52:11,700
and now she started
BBAY several years ago,

1254
00:52:11,700 --> 00:52:13,140
giving back to the community,

1255
00:52:13,140 --> 00:52:16,590
bringing in youngsters
from middle school to Haas

1256
00:52:16,590 --> 00:52:19,980
to educate them about business,
to get them interested,

1257
00:52:19,980 --> 00:52:21,990
so they'll go on to college and all.

1258
00:52:21,990 --> 00:52:24,493
Wonderful person, anyone can vote.

1259
00:52:24,493 --> 00:52:29,310
ChrisKindnessAward.org,
voting goes through Friday.

1260
00:52:29,310 --> 00:52:32,040
If you want to vote for Olive,
that would be wonderful.

1261
00:52:32,040 --> 00:52:34,110
And we need nominations,

1262
00:52:34,110 --> 00:52:36,509
we're seeking nominations all the time.

1263
00:52:36,509 --> 00:52:39,210
Go on our website,
nominate anyone who lives,

1264
00:52:39,210 --> 00:52:41,430
works, or goes to school in Berkeley

1265
00:52:41,430 --> 00:52:43,080
and we're raising money now.

1266
00:52:43,080 --> 00:52:46,950
We now give second and
third prize cash prizes also

1267
00:52:46,950 --> 00:52:49,080
and we're trying to grow
throughout the community

1268
00:52:49,080 --> 00:52:50,400
and beyond Berkeley as well.

1269
00:52:50,400 --> 00:52:53,670
So ChrisKindnessAward.org,
thank you so much, Nora.

1270
00:52:53,670 --> 00:52:56,727
Thank you, Dean, appreciate it, thank you.

1271
00:52:56,727 --> 00:52:59,977
(audience applauding)

1272
00:53:01,131 --> 00:53:02,128
- [Nora] So we know

1273
00:53:02,128 --> 00:53:04,389
that many of you are doing
meaningful and interesting things

1274
00:53:04,389 --> 00:53:05,850
for your local communities,

1275
00:53:05,850 --> 00:53:07,770
for your friends, for your family,

1276
00:53:07,770 --> 00:53:09,600
we want to thank you for all of that,

1277
00:53:09,600 --> 00:53:13,509
for Blake, Yvonne, Eli, Ann,

1278
00:53:13,509 --> 00:53:15,990
thank you for coming,
thank you for listening.

1279
00:53:15,990 --> 00:53:17,610
We hope you are inspired

1280
00:53:17,610 --> 00:53:21,210
